        <Text>The wilderness is Solraheen’s garden. It is a sacred garden. Every littler garden is sacred too. Mandri had seen his fair share of them. He’d walked under the royal palms of Lord Kineal, and he’d nearly drowned in the lordling of Luzee’s terraced falls. He’d seen every garden that people boast about seeing.
And they were all disgusting, those thirsty greenscapes.
Often, there’d be a stripe of atmosphere reflecting off the surface of a stream. This line represented death, or something like that. There might have been more to it, but Mandri knew the truth—people built these gardens to appear gently born. At least, that was the charitable view. The only other explanation was that they derived some perverse enjoyment from putting plants into their ‘proper’ places. Bushes were stuck here. Trees kept there. Flowering weeds were permitted to trim the walkways. A good slaughter every now and then ensured they never grew out of their station. Yes, it was all kept in good order by the brilliance of the human mind. Nature as god intended. Very pretty to look at.
Salavan’s garden was unique. It had no placid stream to symbolize some anagogic screed. There were no trees, or flowers, or artificial boundaries between. No, when Mandri stepped through Salavan’s gate and onto a plain of bone-white pebbles, he stepped into a garden composed entirely of curated stone.
This was a pleasant turn.
Still, he was not impressed, because this garden still obeyed all the rules.
It established a hierarchy of form. The stones here came in a spectrum of sizes, from enormous to flaky specks. They were arranged in such a way so as to draw the eye, or in this case, a person, through a maze of perception and towards what was important. And the play with contrast lacked nuance. Most rules of thumb in art have to do with manipulating contrast. Sharp against soft. Dark against light. So against so. Here, a rippling sea of smooth white pebbles bounced against jagged knots of gray granite, granite which grew in size towards the center of this snow-white field of stone. There, in the god-spot center, stood a towering spike of Fabled Black.
Now that was a surprise.
Fabled Black, the skewering stone. Shard of the firmament. Quintessence of night. If it were a tree, and the pebbles, grass, and the granite, bushes, it all would have been too stilted—but this was the god-killing stone, and so the stasis, the general air of oppression, that was the point.
Mandri walked right up to this black obelisk. He saw his own reflection in its surface sheen, split by streaks of rain. He looked worse than he’d ever been—eyes red and witless, face gaunt, lips cracked. His sodden hair clung tight to his meatless skull. He looked like death. Perhaps everyone who looked into the depths of Fabled Black looked like death.
Pel’s voice rose out of the ether behind him.
“The stone makes the most wondrous pigment.”
Mandri spun around. Standing five feet behind him was that black robed witch, as tall and imposing as ever. But she looked less serious. Or rather, she didn’t look like a demon. Nothing was twisting her genteel airs. Mandri suspected his burgeonsight was dimming.
She looked longingly at the obelisk.
“It makes a black that rivals the crow.”
Mandri dared to sneak a look behind at the spire of Fabled Black. He wanted to ask how anyone could have come into possession of such a thing, and why they dared to keep it outdoors. It was forbidden to possess even the smallest shard of Fabled Black, forbidden even for a Hrkan Lord. 
Pel walked up to this spike and set an elegant hand upon it, caressing it as if it were a prized horse.
“It is wonderful isn’t it?” she said. “Yet it is only a small sliver of the comet which killed Solraheen.”
“How did come to be here?”
“Bribery,” Pel said sternly. “Provisions for the smuggling alone cost Salavan thirty-five silver strings.”
“I see.”
Pel grimaced at Mandri’s critical tone. “You’ll meet him soon enough. But first, you can touch it if you like.”
“No thanks.”
“You are right, there’s no need.” Pel pulled her hand away from the rock. “Merely being in its presence is enough.”
Fabled Black was notorious for its aura of gloom. A small shard of it could make the happiest child feel rotten. Here in such quantity, that feeling crept down to the bone.
“Isn’t it strange that everything that falls from the sky should radiate this sadness?”
“What?”
“This rain…This stone...Either the heavens are a reservoir of despair and these elemental things are infused with it, or this world is a supremely disappointing place, and so things cast down upon it emit a longing to be somewhere else.” He turned to Mandri and his gaze grew stern. “Would you say that’s what you feel right now? A longing to be somewhere else?”
“You could say that.”
“Don’t be so glib. You must admit that the rain would prefer to dance in the clouds. Wouldn’t this stone rather gird the stars than be stuck here in the ground? I think so. You see, the Black is alive. In a very real sense, it is alive, and I can’t wait to show you what it can do. Would you like to see?”
She spared Mandri a beneficent smile. Her teeth did not sparkle as the once did—perhaps the stone, or the long march up the hill was pushing Mandri’s mind back into sobriety. 
“I don’t have a choice, do I?”
“No, you don’t.”
She skirted around Mandri and past the spike of Fabled Black. She was careful to keep her feet out of any puddles in a an odd sort of shuffle, looking to Mandri like a great black cloud tiptoeing its way through nettles.
He followed her, and once she and he were under the roof of the Salavan’s portico, the enormous double doors swiveled open to reveal an enormous man. He height matched Pel’s, and his barrel of a chest was easily thrice the size of Mandri’s own. His great bulk was draped in a white silk robe, and his face was Jandrian through and through—high cheeks, a strong brow, and narrow eyes. The only outlier was his hair, for he had no beard, just fat dimpled cheeks, and instead of the usual scruff of Jandri black, his shoulder-length hair was as white as his robe.
His face was lit with a pleasing smile. “Ahhhhhhh,” he sighed. “My lady returns! And I see you’ve found him. Wonderful.”
Mandri expected Pel to bow out of respect for Salavan’s title, but of course she didn’t. She was a witch. Indeed, she seemed to stand even straighter, and said, “I require a change of robes.”
“Of course,” Salavan replied. He clapped his hands, and a servant boy rushed from a servant’s door, carrying a towel and a long black sheet. He also held a white linen tunic for Mandri. Pel disappeared into the building while Mandri was dried and fitted with this knee-length garb.
It was a bit awkward, being watched by a man with such a title as Lordly Voice.
“I am Salavan,” Salavan said. “And you are the great Mandrameen.”
Mandri nodded, then continued to towel his hair.
“You know,” Salavan said, “I love your work. I was hoping, when I came to Meskalim, that your path would lead you to my door. Wonderful.”
Mandri peered inside Salavan’s house, hoping 
“I take it Pel threatened to kill you if you didn’t come and see me?”
“Something like that.”
“And here you are, seeing me.”
“Here I am.”
“Then you have fulfilled that obligation, and you can leave if you wish.” Salavan’s fat brow pinched up and he added, “I won’t have this tension in my house. You are safe here, and you are free to leave at any time. Or, if you are at all curious about what may lay in store for you, then admit it, and we shall find it out together.”
“I’m not a eunuch.”
Salavan chuckled. His great bulk chuckled along with him. “None could doubt it. Now, would you like to come inside?”
When Mandri hesitated, Salavan scowled back. “Assert yourself,” he said brusquely. “I won’t have any of this meekness in my house. Stand up straight if you can. Sol’s light. You look like you’ve just squeezed out the womb.”
“I’ll go in.”
“That’s not much better,” Salavan said as his whole face scrunched up tight. “but it will have to do. Come.”
He led Mandri inside. They weren’t even two steps past the threshold when Salavan asked, “How do you find my home?”
“It’s nice.”
“You know, it cost me fifty silver strings just to burn the lime for the plaster, and that only accounts for the outer wall. This interior you see here, the plaster alone, that cost…well, I don’t want to go on and on about expenses.” He gave a smug and self-aware smile.
Mandri nodded along. Unlike the garden outside, Salavan’s palace met expectations entirely. Mandri could have been standing inside any number of palaces that scabbed the Hrkan world; tall arched ceilings, wide halls with skinny walls, no ornamentation, everything painted white. No color. The ostentation of color was to be abhorred in favor of natural light, Solraheen’s light. Paintings were the only exceptions, for these were sacred expressions as well. But every painting must be self-contained, bounded by a frame, for it was said that Solraheen would refuse to dwell in a place that presumed to blur the line between human and divine creation. 
The day’s rainy gray was unable to illuminate the vast interior of Salavan’s home. This emptiness was not at odds with the extravagant games that the rich play to prove their wealth—if one is allowed to have only nothing, the question then becomes, how much nothing could one accumulate? The height of Salavan’s ceiling measured of how much emptiness he could afford. Judge the floor—the richer man’s floor bears nothing, not even dirt. A truly rich man could afford to employ a person or persons to always be wiping away the filth tramped in from the street. Salavan’s floor was as white as the sway-away ceiling, and as he and Mandri walked along barefoot, a girl crawled behind on hands and knees with a bowl of water and a brush, scrubbing away.
“Beautiful, isn’t it?” Salavan’s asked.
“Very clean,” said Mandri.
“Yes. Perhaps you will find my gallery stimulating. I’ve some pieces here that you won’t see anywhere else, but that goes without saying.”
“Any of them stolen?”
The accusation put a slight hitch in Salavan’s step. Then the man smiled magnificently, like being accused of theft was a compliment. 
“None are stolen. One does not become a Voice of the Lords by making enemies. I’ve acquired everything I own through legitimate means. I even have something of yours here. One of your best works, I think.”
“Spare me.”
“Don’t be modest, Mandri. I won’t have falseness in my house.”
Salavan clapped his hands and another slave came forth from some narrow orifice, carrying a shallow bowl lined with finger-length wraps of freeweed.
“If paintings aren’t your pleasure, how about a wrap?”
Mandri declined. Salavan seemed genuinely surprised. “You are remarkably lucid,” he said. “You do have that hopeless look about you. I supposed that was, you know, the general malaise of the indigent.”
Salavan selected a wrap for himself, put it in a pocket inside his robe, then waved his slave away. “We shall forgo the freeweed, and perhaps we’ll save the gallery tour for another time. You came here for a purpose, after all.”
“About that,” Mandri said. “I can tell you right now that I’m not a—”
Salavan stopped Mandri mid-sentence with a polite wave of his hand. “You cannot tell me anything. Not even about yourself. I should say that I know more about you than you do.”
“I doubt that.”
“A thing to know about me, Mandri—I am straightforward, and I do not lie because lying wastes time.”
“What is my mother’s name?”
Salavan snorted. “I don’t pollute my mind with such trifles. Neither do you. Consider—do you know the personal name of a lizard? No? But you do know more about a lizard than it knows about itself. Your knowledge of the lizard circumscribes the minutiae of its life to paint a more complete picture. That is how knowledge works. In a way, knowledge is an advanced species of ignorance; we ignore the little details so that we don’t get swamped in a tide of them. Do you understand my meaning?” 
Mandri nodded politely, because one did not reveal their true thoughts to a man so esteemed.
“I can see that you are going to need it explained,” Salavan said. “Come. We must study at least one piece of art. Come.”
Salavan led Mandri through a series of rooms, each with a ceiling higher than the one before. Common to the fashion of the Hrkan elite, the place was sparsely furnished. If there was a table, it was carved from a rough, pale slab of sandstone. If there was a chair, its legs were sanded branches and its seat was woven reed. If there was a tapestry, it was blank, devoid of color and image, for its purpose was to be a frame for the faded subtleties of Solraheen’s light. Cold and gray, today.
Salavan led Mandri into a cavernous room that had a circular hole in its roof. A light rain suffused with silver sunlight streamed down through this hole to pitter-patter in a rainwater pool. All edges of the room were laden with pillows, all of them white, with white tassels.
On the opposite side of the sprinkling rain was a fresco that spanned the entirety of the wall. It was a magnificent work of art in skill and in subject. It depicted Solraheen at the very moment of His victory over evil. He was there, stretched out, as if flying, and his face wore a beatific smile, clearly pleased with the sight of His sword as He plunged it into His brother’s back. In the classic Hrkan style, Solraheen was pure white, and His brother, Schisol, was an ashy black. The army of people surrounding them were a whirlwind were cast in every color imaginable.
“This is my favorite piece.” Salavan said contentedly. “For sentimental reasons, mostly. The god of creation destroying the god of destruction. Shouldn’t it be the other way around? It has so much behind it, if you know what I mean.”
“I don’t.”
“See this yellow?” Salavan said, admiring. “Isn’t it beautiful?”
He was pointing to the golden rays which emanated out from Solraheen’s head. It truly was a fantastic yellow, extraordinarily vibrant, as if it had been painted on mere moments ago.
“Can you guess the pigment?”
“I have no idea.”
“This yellow, it comes from the Gabo cow. Incredibly expensive. The most wasteful pigment imaginable. To make enough for this fresco I had to buy three men to care for fifty cows. I had to put them on a strict diet, the cows. They couldn’t eat anything but this little squeaking bug, called a zuberant. They look like locusts, but they are thick and stubby like your thumb, well, my thumb.”
“I’ve seen them.”
“You buy zuberants in bulk. Then you make a paste out of them, and feed it to the cows. Their bellies have to be stuffed full all at once. That means you have to starve them a bit so they take to that bug-paste like dogs to the bone. The next step has to be timed correctly, because, you see, this radiant pigment comes from the chyme of the cow’s third stomach, so you must be precise with the cutting. You must wait until the chyme extrudes into that stomach, not the first or second stomach, the third stomach, and that’s when you cut open the beast and harvest as much of this yellow slime as you can. Then, you dry it out into a powder, and that is that.”
“Interesting.”
“Once you have the powder, you can sell the meat. But I don’t sell the meat. I let it rot in the sun.”
“Why?”
“Because it feels…” Salavan waved his hand in the air as if to catch the words that could accurately describe what he was thinking. “It feels weighty to have killed a herd of beasts for the explicit purpose of painting my wall. Doesn’t Solraheen look radiant? And now that you know fifty cows died to make it seem so, doesn’t that make the fresco take on a more…oh, I can’t find the words. It feels weighty. It feels more...”
“It doesn’t do anything for me.”
Salavan’s round face lit up. “Hah! It doesn’t, does it?! Well you can’t judge me, boy, no one can. The gods are all dead. And here are the last of them, Schisol and Solraheen, and there—” he pointed to the top of the piece, to the screaming black comet in the sky, “There is the Fabled Black coming to end them both. Such a fine image, no? The quality of the painting is sublime, yes?”
“Sure.”
“Don’t be flippant. It is beautiful. This is Ellag’s hand. I trust you are familiar with her work?”
“I am.”
“She is here, you know. I keep her here to help me find my Mazid. That is why you are here. I have been chosen to be a Minder, so I need my Mazid.”
Salavan’s demeanor shifted into something more serious as he turned his attention away from the fresco and towards Mandri alone. “Tell me, Mandri, do you know what a Mazid is?”
“Of course. Everybody knows.”
“What does everybody know?”
Salavan’s request for clarification suggested the man was seeking some deeper truth about a Mazid’s nature than mere function and appearance. Mandri had seen a few Mazidai from a distance, as they were never far from a Hrkan Lord. They all had a certain slightness of size, and all of them were shrouded in dark robes and never spoke. Mandri had only ever seen one of them up close. It was a young woman, underfed, and her serene expression was couched in generic Hrkan features—thin lips and sad eyes, all in near-genderless proportion, completely unremarkable except for the fact that she could shoot a scorching beam of golden fire out of her mouth.
He finally said, “Everybody knows that a Mazid is a weapon.”
Salavan rolled his eyes. “That is one role a Mazid fulfills,” he said, “But it is better to think of the Mazidai as the tools which Solraheen grants the Lords to help them rearrange the world—to organize the world.”
“Right,” said Mandri, remembering. “A Mazid is endowed with the power to destroy evil.”
Salavan chuckled, as if Mandri had just said something precious and absurd.
“Tell me, Mandri, how can something which does not exist be destroyed?”
“Are you suggesting that evil does not exist?”
“Can you point to it? I can point to you, I can point to this wall, but I cannot point to ‘evil’.”
With that, Salavan put his fat finger up on the fresco and poked Schisol’s belly, right where Solraheen’s sword burst forth. A click sounded from under the floor, and a square of stone at the base of the wall levered open to reveal a narrow stairway descending into darkness. 
“Before we head down,” said Salavan, “I must demand from you your utmost commitment. I, unlike the Solitants, value honesty, so my good character compels me to warn you that there is a chance—a chance—that as we attempt to squeeze your Spark for ripeness, you will die. It is only a chance, and a small one at that, but I want you to consider the thought before you join me.”
Salavan hiked up the hem of his robe and disappeared down into the inky blackness which shrouded the stairwell’s descent. Mandri stared after Salavan, and he must have stared for quite a while, because Salavan’s voice echoed up, saying, “I said consider the thought, not inhabit it!”
Mandri stepped down the stairs and a servant girl bustled out from some hidden passage and closed the hatch behind him.
At the bottom of the stairs was a narrow hall, and at the end of this hall was a cramped room with a low ceiling and rough-cut stone for walls. In the room’s far right corner was a smoldering fire of coals in a bronze brazier. Its red glow splayed out over three three wooden chairs set in the middle of the room, with two chairs facing one. Salavan sat in one of the two, and sitting in the chair next to him was a person draped in a white sheet.
“Don’t look so pale,” Salavan sighed. “I told you not to come down if you weren’t committed. You’ve come, and now you’re here, yes?”
Mandri nodded.
“Good. Sit down.” 
Mandri took the remaining seat, across from Salavan and the veiled stranger. Salavan pulled the wrap of freeweed from his pocket, then he lit it in the brazier’s coals. He puffed it thrice to get it going.
“So!” he said as he slapped his leg to capture Mandri’s attention. “Are you to be my Mazid? Or are you simply a painter who is bored of painting? You’d be surprised how many of those we find.”
Salavan puffed on his wrap.
Mandri simply sat there.
“Are your wits here, Mandri? Are you here?”
Mandri nodded.
“Use your voice. Assert yourself.”
Mandri cleared his throat, then nodded towards the sheeted person and asked, “Who is that?”
“This is Ellag. Or I should say, it was Ellag. She is dead. As I mentioned earlier, I keep her here to aid my search for a Mazid. You see, I am looking for someone who understands what it means to be inspired. I find that Ellag’s presence helps to demonstrate the truth of the matter.”
Salavan’s chair creaked as he laid back into it. He blew a puff of smoke out the side of his mouth, as if the smoke could go anywhere in this cramped room. Between the freeweed and the smoking coals, Mandri was having a hard time finding a clean breath.
Salavan crossed his tree-trunk legs and said, “Tell me, Mandri, what do you think Art is? If you could define it. Define Art.”
Mandri eyed the sheeted woman and asked in turn, “What does that have to with all this?”
“Don’t be coy, Mandri. This is important. You must be eased into the right frame of mind before we move on to the test itself.”
“I’m more concerned about what’s under that sheet.”
“Is that why you don’t want to paint anymore, you think there are more important things to be doing?”
“At the moment, yes.”
“Come now, Mandri, you’ve spent too much time in front of an easel not to have some idea of what it is that you are doing. What is art? What does an artist do?”
Mandri felt he was stumbling into a trap. Or maybe he was already trapped and he didn’t know it. He stuttered and said, “I make… an artist makes an artwork.”
Salavan sighed, then took a long drag from his wrap. He held the smoke in his great big chest, and when he finally exhaled, his round shoulders slumped so far it seemed the essence of life was leaving him.
“You think art is merely a word,” he said. “You think that it is a label that people slap onto things for utility.”
“I didn’t say that.”
“Then say something. I’m trying to help you avoid ending up like Ellag here.”
Salavan puts his arm around Ellag’s shoulder and gave her body a friendly shake. Her sheeted head rolled limply and then settled into the crook of his shoulder as if she were looking to cuddle. The sheet pulled taught over her face and a smear of blood welled up from her forehead to stain the fibers.
Salavan narrowed his eyes at Mandri. The air between them swirled with smoke. 
“Answer my question,” Salavan commanded.
“Is she dead?” Mandri squeaked.
“I’ve already told you. Yes. She is dead. Answer the question.”
“What was the question?” 
Salavan sighed again, then he steadied Ellag back onto her own chair so that he could lean forward and free his hands for explanation. He said, “Ellag thought that art was about the artist. A person goes out into the world and has some incredible experience—like you’re having now. It changes them in some important, fundamental way. They look at the world differently. But how could any of their friends or family know that any of this has occurred? The change is internal, it is not written on the skin. There might be some new sparkle in the eye, their behavior might be different, but none of that will ever communicate the depth of what has changed inside the mind. Consider a woman crying—for what reason does she cry? She tells you her child has died, but you’ve never had a child, Mandri, so how could you understand? To understand, you would have to have experienced it for yourself. This is the problem which art purports to solve. A work of art provides a surrogate experience which allows us to break through that impenetrable barrier between our minds.”
Not one word of that made it to Mandri’s ear. He was too focused on finding a chance to flee. He suspected could make a dash for the stairs with a head start, because Salavan was so wrapped up the freeweed’s smoke.
Salavan said, “That’s what Ellag thought. She thought that art is a thing an artist does to let everyone else know what’s going on inside. Does that make sense?”
“It’s very sentimental.”
“Sentimental, yes, that would be a word for it. Unfortunately, it is completely and utterly wrong. Look how wrong it can be.”
Salavan bent down, grabbed the foot of Ellag’s sheet, and in one quick flourish he flipped it over the back of her chair to reveal her corpse.
Her dead head bobbed and settled, and as it did a trickle of blood dripped out of the empty sockets that had once held her eyes. The belly of her tunic had been ripped apart, while the belly itself had been carved open with surgical precision—skin folded back like a book to reveal a cavity under her ribs. Emptiness through to her spine. She was hollowed out. 
“Steady, Mandri. Steady yourself…now, looking at Ellag, you might suppose that I think I am an artist, and that this,” he put his hand on Ellag’s skull and twisted it about in a perverse display of puppetry. “This is me communicating to you in a way that lets you experience, in a profound way, who I am and what it’s like to be me.”
He let go of Ellag’s head, and it slumped down onto her collarbone.
“But that would be a misunderstanding. Consider—why isn’t speech, casual conversational speech like we’re having now, why isn’t that considered to be an art? I am manipulating my throat, tongue, teeth, and lips to shape a string of sounds for you to experience. Sentences are things that can break down that barrier between our minds, yes?”
At this point the freeweed was having its way with Salavan. His thick-armed gesticulations were growing frenetic. He cut the air with a slicing hand and declared, “No. I am not an artist. I am many things, but I am not an artist.”
“You’re a murderer.”
“I’m not a murderer, either.”
Salavan took another big drag from his freeweed. The room was so small, and the smoke was so thick, that Mandri supposed it was getting to him too.
“Actually,” Salavan said, “that’s not true, I am a murderer. But I think you’re referring to Ellag, here. I did not kill her. She died because she thought art was about the artist. She thought that the painter was important. She thought far too much of herself.” He was churning his words into the air with his free hand, as if mixing his musings with the smoke would bring out some flavor of the truth.
“You’re insane,” said Mandri.
“It is good that you should say that. Ellag was never able to make that step. She was too…embodied. Like this bundle of freeweed. Also, she was frightened.” He leaned forward a little in his seat. “See, if you look into the Black when you’re frightened, you’re bound to see frightening things.” 
Salavan made an explosion with his fingers, pretending to burst his eyes.
“Her eyes exploded?” Mandri asked in wonder.
“They did. You can see the stain here on the floor. It was fascinating.”
“What about her stomach?”
“That was me,” Pel said, sneaking up from behind, spooking Mandri near out of his skin.
She drifted by, a wisp of black, and stood beside Salavan. Her cowled head nearly brushed the ceiling.
“I wished to query the girl’s stomach.”
“All done after the fact,” Salavan assured. “But we shouldn’t get distracted.” He poked these words with his wrap of freeweed, and this shook a clump of ash free from the glowing tip.
“No, we shouldn’t,” Pel agreed. “We should begin.” 
“Of course.”
Salavan set his freeweed onto the corner of his seat, then stood up. He moseyed over to the far left corner of the room, hidden by Ellag’s shadow. There he struggled with a square stone slab which was as black as the darkness from which he pulled it. He propped the massive thing up against his thighs and waddled it over. He laid it down flat at Mandri’s feet. He then shuffled back into the dark to fetch three three clay jars, and set them next to the black stone panel. Each jar was filled with a black paint.
Pel pulled from her robe a paintbrush. Its handle was short compared to the length of the brush head, which was as long as Mandri’s forearm. It looked more like a whip than a paintbrush. She handed it to Mandri and said, “Paint a picture.”
“A picture of what?”
“If I may,” Salavan interjected.
Pel stood back to give Salavan room.
“Don’t think about what you are painting,” he said. He crouched to evenly meet Mandri’s eye. “Don’t give yourself that privilege. Don’t think about what should or shouldn’t be. You need to simply start painting.”
“You want me to figure things out as I go?”
“No. Don’t figure anything out. You are merely a tool. True art creates itself. It is reckoned with on its own terms. It is its own experience. It communicates nothing but what it is. You kneel there—” Salavan pointed to the floor in front of Mandri. “And you become the tool by which the work creates itself.”
Mandri squinted in confusion. If he thought about nothing, then he would paint nothing. Even if he wanted to paint something, it would be hopeless, because in this dim light he wouldn’t be able to see what he was doing. And there were only the three black paints to put on a black slab of rock.
Salavan returned to his seat, and the sheer weight of him plopping onto his too-small chair disturbed Ellag’s corpse. She slumped forward over her knees. Her limp wrists smacked onto the floor.
“This test,” Salavan said thoughtfully, “Will determine how skilled you are at removing yourself from yourself.” 
Mandri nodded as if Salavan was making sense. He decided he better get it over with. Perhaps if he swirled some of the paint on the slab, then Salavan would let him leave. He knelt down before the black stone surface and thought about what he should do.
With no palette, the stone itself would have to be the palette. It wasn’t like he was going to run into trouble mixing paints if the only color was black. One by one one, he picked up the clay jars and, trembling, poured their contents onto the stone surface. The first paint came out of its jar in a clump. It slopped onto the stone like a sandy gel. Mandri could see little granules of Fabled Black sparkling in the firelight. The next paint was a clean, syrupy goo that drizzled out of the jar. The last paint was so thin that he had to be careful pouring it out, lest it splash all over the place. Thankfully, the surface of the stone was ever so slightly bowled.
When Mandri was done with all this, he cast a side-eyed glance at Salavan to see if the man approved of what he was doing.
Salavan glared back. “Don’t look at me, look at the work.”
Mandri’s breathing grew nervous. The smoke in the air was stifling. He fanned his tunic—light as the linen was, the room's heat had become unbearable. He’d been putting off the realization that Salavan was looking for him to do a specific something, and that if he didn’t do it, he would not be allowed to leave. That realization was now coming on so strong it was paralyzing.
“What will happen if I fail?” he asked.
Salavan shook his head and said, “Think, instead, of what will happen if you should succeed. If you can let yourself be used by the work, think of what you can become!”
“But what should I paint?”
Salavan took another drag of his freeweed and reclined back into his chair. He looked away, studied his own smoke, as if he was alone in the room. Pel was still staring.
Mandri turned his attention back to the slathered-black stone. 
What could he possibly paint with black, on top of black, on top of black?
He poked the long-haired brush into the sandier gel and spread it around. It did not mix with the other paints, indeed it pushed right through them. The thinner paints in turn flooded into the grooves left by the brush’s passing.
He sat back on his heels and studied the whorl he’d made. The sheen of the red-orange firelight played with each paint differently. It stuck softly to the fine grained gel, it stippled the syrupy fluid, and it hardly touched the thinnest paint. Wherever the thinnest paint pooled, the image was truly black.
Mandri began to push and pull the paints around to build an image out of the light, as a sculptor might build an image out of shadows. He didn’t much care about what he was making, the brush hairs were too long and too limp to be too deliberate.
What was he making?
Black pools welled up like the hollows of human eyes.
A face.
Why not?
He pulled a stripe of shadow to form up the upper lip.
A mound of the gel brought out the cheeks.
It was coming along.
A long and powerful face.
Mandri swirled the brush around in an eye socket, trying to find an eye.
Suddenly, there it was, an eye of firelight.
It blinked.
Mandri startled backwards in fright. He quickly gathered his wits and peered with disbelief down at that fire-flickering eye.
A thin stream of black ran down below the upper lip, opening the mouth.
Was there a tongue in there? A black snake of a tongue glinting in the back of the throat?
Yes. There it was.
“Do you see this?” Mandri asked, but no response came.
He looked up to see if Salavan was even looking, but the man wasn’t there. Neither was Pel. Neither were the chairs, or even walls—there was only Mandri, the coal fire, his painting, and a void.
The face he’d painted began to extrude out of the stone. Fabled Black dripped down its ashen cheeks. Mandri scrambled backwards on all fours, and when the Black head was fully in the round it tilted upright.
It opened its eyes. They were filled with a rainbow fire.
Mandri’s Spark tugged against his stomach
He screamed, but no sound came. And now he could not close his mouth. His jaw was locked. The Black head jumped flew off the slab, angling right for him. It flew as Pel had flown, straight and eager. It smacked right into Mandri’s head and exploded into a splash into Black paint. The force of it threw Mandri backwards, and backwards again, and while he tumbled the paint dripped down his throat. He tumbled and tumbled, until finally, he tumbled right out of the void.
He landed hard on stone. It knocked the breath out of him. He choked and sputtered on the paint. Then he opened his eyes and saw Salavan’s wild face hovering over his own.
“What did you see?!” Salavan asked as his hands clenched Mandri’s throat.
“He saw Him,” Pel declared.
Salavan glanced at the painted slab, then muttered a single, breathless word, “Incredible...”
Mandri tried to pull himself free from Salavan’s grip, but the man roared and threw his great weight down upon Mandri, pinning him against the ground. Mandri heaved and wiggled but it was all for naught.
“Hold still!” Salavan groaned. “You…must…hold…still!”
Salavan’s plumping smile savored every desperate wheeze.
“I knew your Spark was ripe the moment I saw you,” he whispered.
A few juddering moments later, and Mandrameen went limp.</Text>
